Welcome back to to yet another updated Gren Maju build. With the way the current and likely meta is going to shape once BODE becomes TCG legal, I felt the need to shift from a handtrap Golden Castle based build to a more grindy and even more LVL 8 oriented build. Crossout Designator made handtraps even less effective as well all know. Also with the current meta running more Veiler and Imperms, the OTK that would often be provided by Dragubilon and Numeron Dragon is a lot harder to achieve, and Golden Castle simply burns too much through a 40 card build to risk using anymore.

The deck has seen a marked increase in LV:8's with the additions of Gadarla (vital for Barrier Statue spammers), Gamecial and Alpha. Kaiju's are often my go to to get rid of annoyingly tough to remove omni-negates and other interruptions (Dragoon/Enforcer/Baroness/Ultimatness.. you get the idea). Looping Alpha with Kaiju's is often a good way to eat through several layers of interruption and Alpha being a 3k beatstick allows it to clean up most of what is left. With this increase in LV:8's brings additional drawing power in the form of Trade-In, being useful not only to draw additional cards, but also activate the Danger monster effects should the need arise. Interrupted Kaiju Slumber provides both removal as well as ensuring I can get to a vital Kaiju to further prevent the opponent being able to regain a board. Gizmek/Eater Of Millions and Pot Of Desires as we all know do the job of deck thinning and banishing to allow Gren Maju to swing. Additional facedown removal from Eater is also at times of great benefit. Eater has been moved up from 1 in my Golden Castle builds to 2, to have a more balanced method of winning. Lightning Storm, Harpie's and Pankratops provide excellent removal as well.

Not much really needs to be said about the side deck. I'm pretty much happy with it as is. Dingirsu/Zeus are as strong as they've always been with non-targeting and non-destructive removal. Sanaphond has really come into it's own, as shutting off graveyard revival prevents Enforcer from coming back via it's own effect, as well as shutting down a great deal of the meta's ability to rebuild boards from the grave. Lancelot is surprisingly good with it's ability to poke directly for 2k damage. With life points likely to be low on the opponents end most of the time, this can often be critical. The added negating of any type of activation is a little bonus as well. N'tss to punish Dogmatika. Knightmare's Phoenix, Unicorn and BLS can come up from time to time, but Zeroboros/Accesscode are mainly there as additional win cons and to be honest lack of any real alternatives that fit with the deck. Out of everything in the Extra, these two I can't say have ever come up, nor have there been situations where they could've helped. But you never know, may find some uses at some point.

Dimension Shifter is sat in the side deck. Although still immensely strong and crippling to the vast majority of decks, without knowing the impact of Flunder's on the meta, I would rather have a reasonably solid 40 card main deck that is decently effective against everything (of course the die roll greatly skews this) rather than have a few cards that are utterly useless Game 1 when dealing with what could be frequent matchup. Ra Sphere is 3 Kaiju's in one, and is one of the few cards capable of flat out cleaning Drytron and the monster portion of Phantom Knight boards, which could otherwise prove tricky, if not impossible to get around. Can also come in handy against Swordsoul, as they can have three monsters on board as well. Being a normal summon is also helpful should I walk into Barrier Statue +2 monster boards, and doesn't usually interfere with the deck's strategy, as everything bar Gren Maju is a special summon anyway. Double Twins and Red Reboot are additional backrow coverage, whilst DD Ground, Summon Limit and Imperial Order all provide the ability to completely stun all the match ups i'm likely to face.

